The Week in Feedback=E2=80=A6
-----------------------

On beauty dupes: =E2=80=9CI enjoyed
Rachel=E2=80=99s take on dupes ( https://puck.news/charlotte-tilbury-is-fed=
-up-with-dupes/?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F17%2F25%29&u=
tm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_=
action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) and wanted =
to throw another hat into the ring full of opinions. Based on the work I do=
 on Ulta, brands that are copied are very much impacted by dupes, so much s=
o that Ulta delays launching the dupe as long as possible so it can maintai=
n sales of the more expensive item. The problem is that Ulta can't wait too=
 long
because it=E2=80=99s competing with Amazon and many others willing to jump =
on the dupe as soon as it=E2=80=99s available. In the case of the Dior lip =
oil, an Ulta manager I speak with frequently said that when MCoBeauty=E2=80=
=99s dupe was introduced, Dior=E2=80=99s sales immediately dropped off a cl=
iff. I imagine a lot depends on where the item is being sold and the averag=
e income of the customer. Dupes have become commonplace, and I=E2=80=99m no=
t sure how brands fight back, but I think doing nothing isn=E2=80=99t a goo=
d course.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A
beauty executive

=C2=A0

On Charlotte Tilbury: =E2=80=9COne of the most chaotic, disorganized beauty=
 companies. It lacks strategy or any broad vision other than saying they wa=
nted to make lots of money. They really want to make skincare a focus and m=
oneymaker, but the customer just didn=E2=80=99t care. Interesting to see wh=
at happens to them!=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A consultant

=C2=A0

On Elisa Lipsky-Karasz=E2=80=99s exit from WSJ.: =E2=80=9CThat sucks for El=
isa, but if she can survive being [former Harper=E2=80=99s Bazaar editor-in=
-chief] Glenda Bailey=E2=80=99s assistant, she can survive anything! (Just =
kidding, we love Glenda.)=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A former Harper=E2=80=99s Bazaa=
r editor=C2=A0

=C2=A0

On Vuori, ughhhh: =E2=80=9CYou mentioned in an episode
of Fashion People ( https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/fashion-people/id=
1741589082?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F17%2F25%29&utm_co=
ntent=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_actio=
n&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) a while back tha=
t you didn=E2=80=99t know who was actually wearing Vuori. I live in Houston=
 and I can tell you that there=E2=80=99s a ton of it here and throughout Te=
xas. It=E2=80=99s very much a thing with guys who listen to Joe Rogan, do C=
rossFit, buy raw milk for their kids, wear mesh hats, and drive Rivians.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94A technology manager at a
non-technology company

On the Proenza-to-Loewe deal: =E2=80=9CAm I the only person concerned about=
 what this means for men=E2=80=99s fashion? Blazy goes to Chanel and is rep=
laced by a womenswear designer at Bottega. Sarah Burton, primarily a gown d=
esigner, goes to Givenchy. If you look across the spectrum of high-fashion =
brands right now, it=E2=80=99s not great. Kim Jones=E2=80=99 influence is s=
tagnating. We have Prada (and it=E2=80=99s
incredible, thank god!), and until now we=E2=80=99ve had Loewe and Bottega =
very much leading the conversation in terms of progressing where men=E2=80=
=99s fashion was going, except for Balenciaga which is now probably the mos=
t influential across the board but has been dominating for 10 years. And we=
 lost Hedi! And Dries retired!=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A writer

On Proenza leaving Proenza: =E2=80=9CThrilled for the boys, but sad about t=
he NYFW cancellation this
season because I was looking forward to that potential menswear debut. But =
looks like we=E2=80=99ll get it at Loewe so can=E2=80=99t be too mad.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94An editor

=E2=80=8A

Until Monday,

Lauren

